{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"08ab8b55-1dfb-4dd8-bb31-979b959f7cee","content":"The working directory is empty, so there's no repo-specific documentation to reference. Here's the general guidance:\n\n### Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\nNativeAOT apps don't ship with `createdump` (that's a CoreCLR tool). On macOS, use the OS-level crash reporting instead:\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** — run `ulimit -c unlimited` in your shell before launching the app.\n\n2. **Check `/cores/`** — macOS writes core files to `/cores/core.<pid>`. Ensure the directory exists and is writable:\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n3. **Check Apple crash logs** — macOS also generates `.ips` crash reports at:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n4. **Use `lldb` to analyze** the core dump:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n5. **If core dumps aren't appearing**, macOS SIP (System Integrity Protection) may be blocking them. Check with `csrutil status`. On newer macOS, you may also need to set:\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.coredump=1\n   ```\n\n6. **For richer .NET diagnostics**, consider setting `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1` and `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4` environment variables — though these rely on `createdump` being present, so they won't apply to NativeAOT.\n\n**TL;DR**: Rely on macOS native core dumps (`/cores/`) and Apple crash reports (`DiagnosticReports/`), then analyze with `lldb`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0e993a9d-662d-4772-b412-91d9219249bc","outputTokens":448,"requestId":"7841:2671F1:4A5561:56103D:69FA9E33"},"id":"3055ff23-8dda-4733-bb8d-f039cefe2690","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:49:50.231Z","parentId":"24ce8fbf-f775-4416-94d8-bc77d086c7db"}
